‹g¬]<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1293";s:4:"name";s:5:"Cough";s:4:"slug";s:5:"cough";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1293";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3959:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">A cough is a general reflex action that clears off mucus or foreign irritants from the throat. On an average, a cough that lasts for less than 21 days is acute (mild) in nature while the one that continues for longer can be chronic or a sign of an impending illness.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Coughing to free the throat from mucus is generally an infrequent action, although certain medical conditions can trigger a frequent occurrence.</span>

<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A cough is caused by different conditions, both severe and mild.</span>

<b>Some of the causes of coughs are:</b>

<b>To clear the throat:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The standard way of clearing the throat is through coughing. Any time your airways are clogged with dust, mucus, and other unwanted particle, a cough is a reflex process of clearing the particles and making air flow freely for better breathing.</span>

<b>Bacteria and viruses: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">The highest cause of a cough is through respiratory tract infections like colds and flu. Most infections of the Respiratory tract are usually caused by a virus.</span>

<b>Smoking:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> A very common cause of a cough. Most of the coughs caused by smoking are often chronic in nature. It's also known as a "smoker's cough"</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">¬†</span><b>Treating A Cough</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A cough can be treated in different ways, depending on the type. For adults, self- treatments can be done at home.</span>

<b>Self-treatment</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A viral-induced cough cannot be treated with antibiotics. However, below are some lifestyle changes you can implement:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Drink more water to stay hydrated.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">When sleeping, keep an extra pillow on your head for elevation.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use cough drugs to clear your throat.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always gargle with hot salt water, to which turmeric has been added, to clear off mucus and foreign irritants.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Regularly add ginger or honey to hot tea to reduce your cough and clear your throat.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Can your diet improve your symptoms?</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Generally, a healthy diet can speed up recovery because it fuels your body with the needed nutrients to perform at its optimal.</span>

<b>Below are lists of foods that promise to tame your cough:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Honey and ginger juice decoction</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pineapple</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Chicken soup</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Liquorice root tea</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> ¬† ¬† ¬† Tea made of tulsi leaves and crushed peppercorns</span></li>
</ul>
